segments.text: Well, when we were choosing between the College Board and the American College Testing Code, Dean Hubert told me, he said, now, Austin, you've got to structure this thing where these people that you have examine these tests, that they feel that they're not wasting their time.
And I said, yes, sir, we'll do that.
So if
We chose the College Board, and I use the word we because it was chosen by the deans and the heads of departments all over the campus.
The Counseling Center didn't choose the College Board, although we felt that that was the one that was better suited for our needs.
Well, this was a fine program that Dr. Wayne Hall had.
You see, he had a pragmatic, a practical
measurement of what we were doing and how much economics.
Oh, Chalk, you know Chalk, yeah?
Chalk would be in my, he'd be in our center the morning the test would be.
And he would have his list of his men in order.
And he said, this is the greatest thing that ever happened to me.
He said, I've always wondered, how good a job are we doing?
And, oh, that economics department was very high.
Biology was very high.
But a lot of, only,
Well, we had a little trouble with agriculture.
But Dr. Wayne Hall, being in agriculture, he asked these young men, he said, are you scientists?
And they said, well, yes.
He said, all right.
These are science tests.
He said, what kind of a scientist are you?
Are you a biologist?
Are you, you know, this or that?
And pretty soon the students saw that what he was telling them was that you may be a plant physiologist, but you take the course, you take the test that will measure plant physiology.
But they won't call it plant physiology.
There are not that many taking it.
But if you look at the questions, you'll find it there.
Well, it was a shame, but now, we even had Berkeley.
Berkeley sent a professor, full professor, who spent three days with us studying what we had done with these measures.
And he said, how in the world did you get your profs to do it?
Well, now Haskell, that goes back to our heritage.
Now, did you find good continuity during these years between the different vice presidents for academics?
Was there good continuity of interest by each of them in, whether we called it the Counseling and Testing Service, the Academic Counseling Center, was there good continuity in there?
I think that it was to the extent that the person who was in the office at that time understood the contributions that a guidance center can make.
You know, some people think a guidance center is somewhat for children.
And they don't see the implications.
You did, I remember.
Wayne Hall did.
Now, Dr. Calhoun, once he was able to get acquainted with what our situation was, Dr. Calhoun was a strong supporter of the, oh, I think old Mac Prescott got in real trouble
because he kept bad mouthing the summer conferences.
And I understand Dr. Calhoun read and write that to him and said he didn't want to hear any more of it.
Well, Dr. Calhoun told me, he said, Austin, you ought to feel pretty good when you can have a program where people pay to come see it and hear it.
And it doesn't cost us anything.
We just get to do it.
I think Dr. Calhoun was very much interested.
Now, when this got into what to me was a difficult position, Dr. Colgus was pushing harder and harder for a counseling center.
But that word meant different, had a different meaning to him.
Yes.
And he was not an academic man.
The real problem for him was that the academic people, the counseling was in
The academic effort of the university, I think, is where it belongs.
That was my personal feeling.
I think that it's like in our high school.
We should never have thrust the drug problem on high school counselors.
They're not trained sufficient for that.
it ruins their relationship to make contribution in the afternoon.
I know you understood that years ago because we talked about it on some of our problems.
I think Dr. Byers simply did not have a background and now this
But now this changed some, because I think he had a granddaughter that had some real problems in school, and the counselor was able to help the person, so he began to see a little bit there.
Now, when I was moved under
Now that occurred about when?
That occurred all along about 75.
So that's about the time, that's either Calhoun's last years?
That was his last year.
Now Dr. Calhoun told me, as I remember,
that he said, Austin, I'm going to put you over under Ed Cooper, as long as Ed Cooper is dean of the records.
I think he meant Coles.
You helped by telling Coles.
No one has ever told you you couldn't have a counseling center.
Of course, now, Coles told me, he said, I don't want your staff, I just want your money.
I thought, well, he's honest.
I came of the background
where the guidance is a part of the educational system.
It is not a part of the student life system.
That is my background.
Let's do a long view now.
Based on your experience,
What were the important decisions in the area where you were involved or related to it that you think were key positive decisions?
And if there were any important negative ones, what were the key negative decisions that were made?
Well, I think that we were fortunate in having a background of
Well, the basic division.
The basic division could be looked upon as somewhat of a guidance.
That added to the record of the academic people working with the student.
The fact that we worked closely with the cohort was necessary.
I think the ROTC movement would tell you now that it worked out for the best of the university and the student.
Instead of trying to stubbornly shove the core onto the university, let it find its place.
I feel like that we were able to acquaint professors with what the services can be provided a professor that will make his work more effective.
Sometimes that's helping in research of student characteristics.
Sometimes it's like in the, well, the summer conferences.
The fellow who had charge of freshman English, the setting up the sections.
Haskell, in the last year, after I retired, I went back one summer and helped them with these.
conferences by taking groups of students.
I found out was this young man said to me, he said, I need some help.
He said, I put my program through twice for my request for courses and all I'm able to register in is English and physical education.
And he said, what am I going to do?
He said, I got to call my father in Chicago and tell him that I'm going to go to school, but I only can take two courses.
Well, Haskell, that was unnecessary.
We developed just a number of controls of these students.
And I remember one of my first
occurrences of this type.
They had the associate dean's meeting on Saturday morning after the last and apparently there was a big mess up on no sections and all of this and Dr. Calhoun had called these people together
And Dr. Calhoun said, what in the world caused this?
And Lannis Holt said, I don't know, but I can tell you this, that if you had called Austin Curry, he could have told you within at least 30 or 40 of how many students would be needing that course.
And Dr. Calhoun said, well, when could he have done this?
He said he's kept it all summer.
Well, that was a flaw of Haskell that I don't know, I'm sure Lannis remembered, but that was not necessary.
So that's an example of a service that is available and could have been used, but the person didn't know it.
Now this fellow that handled the English sections, he heard about what we were doing.
So he comes over to the counseling center and we start giving him the fingers.
And he said, he said, I'll tell you what, it beats having a yelling match with being beaten.
But I don't know how this, whether this is answering what we're saying or not.
The University Counseling Center should be one that it's a service.
And it should be structured in a way that it can help people help themselves.
It's not a crutch.
It is not judgmental.
It, it should do good research.
I was kind of amused out here after they, I knew that when they merged, I was a little surprised that shuttle mechanics merged those two.
Because they had too much not in common.
Gradually, within about two years, I think it was, all of the counseling staff had resigned or moved somewhere else.
There is no reason.
Well, the interesting thing is that at the University of Texas, while we were merging, they were separated.
If you were hired as a consultant today to give advice about the area that you knew best, what would be your advice to the university today?
From my field, which really where my real interest lies is in career counseling.
They still have the same thing they had when I came in 1952.
They have the problem of the undecided student.
attempted to help it by making group guidance courses where a student would take a course and then we would carry them through a frequency.
Now, Haskell, we were not great shots at this, but we did not have many who had not made a decision by the second semester.
Now they have people still struggling around in the late sophomore year, as I understand it.
And I think one of the complicating factors now also is that some of the colleges are now setting up a numerical limit on how many they will allow to come into their program.
Yes.
So here are some students then kind of in no man's land or no woman's land.
And where do they go and what do they do?
Your advice, as I'm understanding it, would be that there be, and I'll give it a generic title, a counseling center having to do with academics and with professional goals in life.
Yes.
where that there might be somewhere else a counseling center that helped young people work on their personal problems.
But these are two different units.
Where would be the best place for the academic counseling center, as we're now organized, where would it be located?
Who should that
Well, I think it should be in the academic structure.
Because to me, the preparation of a person for a profession is academic.
It is not student life.
If a person is having a drug problem,
then they should treat that by the people who are qualified in the medical profession and come back to the... You see, what we're trying to do is somewhat like it is in the public schools.
We're trying to solve every problem a person has.
without any relationship to are we suited for it?
Do we have the facilities?
Do we have the staff?
It's the same with, we need to work out some kind of a program where the person can be aware that
If they are not doing well in a program, then people in my field would help them find out why.
Is it because you don't understand?
Is it because you've taken the wrong courses?
These are not things that are related to sex, and I'm not poking fun here, but we need to get help to students in the area in which competency can be seen on both sides.
Now, Texas University, they're pretty screwed.
They have encouraged many freshmen to go to a two-year college.
First one thing, there are several options there.
I'm afraid that we take students, and I don't mean this critically, but we take students
And we don't have a program for them.
And they don't know what the program is.
So that is the dilemma.
There are more, as I understand it, that is Hope's daughter hedging it up.
I understand that General Studies, I think they call it.
It shouldn't be much different than General Curriculum.
They are in there.
Old sophomore?
And that's no good.
I mean, I don't know.
I don't want to sound like I know all the answers, but we are, we may be confusing things to the student about what we do in this area.
I doubt if there's any particular help on the campus to what I'm saying.
Again, looking at the broad view, why has A&M made the progress it has made?
A&M's a much different school now than what it was when you first arrived back here.
What were the reasons, why did A&M
make the progress it made?
Well, I think that, now, A&M has always, to me, has been honest about what it was doing.
You see, when I came back in 52, we had Math 100, English 100, Chemistry 100.
That was because there were people who needed it.
Now, in about two or three years, that began to fade out because the public schools got back into control, the families reorganized, and young people were coming who were better qualified.
Now, we did not give in on standards.
You know, you were here in then, lots of universities bent, and I used to have a difficulty at the college board meeting because I took a firm stand on that, that you will never put out
a medical doctor by letting them study medicine just because they really wanted to or what have you.
Well, we've got to be honest with them.
We've got to say, you know, John, you have some good qualities here.
There's this fellow.
I did some work for the dental college in Houston in this respect.
And they sent this young man up to us.
He was an A&M undergraduate by his degree, and he was studying dentistry.
It was the second year.
It's very serious.
when the staff, the teaching staff for the dental school has to drop a student.
It's a kind of a, well, it upsets everyone.
There's a lot of money put into that.
Well, this young man, he came out to see us.
And so he said, I know why I'm here.
and I appreciate any help you can do.
So we gave him a routine screening and we suggested to him that he take another look at his background and that he work with children.
That could be in elementary schools,
It could be in a different kind.
But that would be an area where he would probably be very happy.
And I looked this man's name up the other day in the Aggie dictionary, I call it.
And this fella is now in charge of the Head Start program in the state of Colorado.
He's been up there for whatever, a decade.
But that's what I mean.
What a university owes to me owes a service to a student that if they're not meeting the terms of the goal that they have, the profession, we should not just kick them out.
But we ought to identify them, work with them,
and help them leave the city.
As we're getting near the end now, what I'm really asking are parts of the university that are dearest to your heart, and let me ask it in this manner.
Let's make believe someone handed you a million-dollar check and said, you can give this check, you must give this money to Texas A&M, but you've got to decide what it would be spent for.
If you were going to be generous to A&M, for what purpose would you want your generosity used?
Well, I feel like, and of course I revert to my biases, I feel like that
We do have a strong counseling center on the campus, but it is not strong in the area of career planning.
I don't mean that critically, but it just isn't.
I would visualize that there would be, well, President Rutter's admonition, there would be a center
for career planning.
There would be, that would be open.
It would be open to students.
I used to do this.
I used to, I'd have people from Amarillo write me and want to bring their son or daughter to the A&M campus for counseling, vocational counseling.
I said, no, that's a long trip.
Go to your high school counselor.
Tell her that I said that I was well aware of how her workload is.
But would she be willing to administer the test to the student back at Amarillo
And we would share the findings with her.
And oh, I never had one turned down.
They all, you know, that got out.
One of the problems we had in this program was that at first, we were having a lot of students not show up.
And I couldn't believe that.
But when we looked into it, we found that this is what happened.
These people in Dallas, wherever, they talk together.
These people that keep up.
And so they said, let's send Johnny down.
Let's let him apply to A&M.
And then he goes through this guidance program.
And they don't have anything like that at SMU or at this.
And so that's when we had to sort of start tying it up more.
But I feel like that first, the cost of an education is tragic, but it's getting to where it's unreasonable.
Secondly, there simply is not
Well, the student, I don't know, the student just, the age problem, I think one of the problems is that youngsters do not have the advantages of experiences.
that youngsters had of the same age several years ago.
So we need to work closely, A&M will work closely with the academic counselors in the high school.
I think they will come to this.
And the third thing would be that they would help the student
if they were here and it didn't look good.
Now, the fourth thing I think is that the university needs to have a continuing relationship in this field.
We could make some fine contributions to the whole field of knowledge of college choice.
career choice, this sort of thing.
If we could work on past the, well, I've worked with graduate students, master's degree candidates.
